Stay at home
Only go outside for food, health reasons or work (but only if you cannot work from home)
If you go out, stay 2 metres (6ft) away from other people at all times
Wash your hands as soon as you get home
Do not meet others, even friends or family.
You can spread the virus even if you don’t have symptoms.

Cases of coronavirus (COVID-19) have been confirmed in Malta. The Maltese authorities have introduced a number of measures to limit the spread of the virus.
All incoming flights to Malta have been suspended. If you live in the UK and are currently visiting Malta, you’re strongly advised to return now by commercial means. Don’t run the risk of getting stranded.
The Maltese authorities have introduced a number of measures in response to the coronavirus (COVID-19) pandemic. You should comply with any additional screening measures put in place by the authorities.
On 13 March Malta introduced a mandatory 14 day self-quarantine period for all arrivals into Malta. This affects tourists and returning residents. Asymptomatic visitors can choose to either enter mandatory self-quarantine or to return to their country of origin as soon as possible. If you leave Malta you must travel directly from your accommodation to the airport where you will be thermally screened.
The Maltese Government have a coronavirus advice page and a coronavirus website which gives the latest updates. A helpline is also available on 111.
If you have symptoms, even if mild, you should contact the public health helpline on 111 and follow their instructions.
Quarantine is being enforced by spot checks and large fines. See the government’s coronavirus advice page for further information.
Schools, childcare centres and other educational institutions are closed as are museums and tourist sites. All restaurants and bars are closed except for take-away and/or deliveries.
Public gatherings of more than 3 people, who are not members of the same household, are banned and social distancing of 2m is encouraged. Vulnerable people including those over 65 should stay at home. Full information is available on the coronavirus advice page .
Further information on coronavirus, including advice on preparing for foreign travel and helping reduce the spread of the virus, is available from Public Health England and on the TravelHealthPro website.
